It looks like you're asking for a Mathematica module that implements an ECDSA-like digital signature scheme. You've provided the code for the elliptic curve operations and some starting parameters, but there may still be some issues with your code due to syntax and conceptual mistakes.

Let's create a Mathematica module that takes textual input (`txt`), the order of the base point (`q`), and a random number `k` and produces a digital signature `(r, s)`. The hash of the text will be computed using MD5 as you have done, but please keep in mind that MD5 is not recommended for cryptographic purposes due to its vulnerabilities.

The digital signature scheme works as follows:

1. Compute the hash of the document (`EE`).
2. Select a random integer `k` from `[1, q-1]`.
3. Compute the elliptic curve point `R = k * P`, where `P` is the base point.
4. Compute `r` as the x-coordinate of `R` modulo `q`. If `r` is `0`, restart with a different `k`.
5. Compute `s = k^(-1) * (EE + r * s) mod q`. If `s` is `0`, restart with a different `k`.

Below is a revised version of your code, consolidated into a single module named `GenerateSignature`:

```mathematica
GenerateSignature[txt_, q_, k_] := Module[
  {EE, p, a, b, iI, P, R, s, r, c, EllipticAdd, Eliptic},

  (* Provided parameters *)
  a = 0; b = 808; p = 2537140233079;
  iI = 17; P = {2198812211451, 2124337351910};

  (* Define the identity element for the group *)
  O = {0, 0};

  (* Define the EllipticAdd function *)
  EllipticAdd[P_List, Q_List] := Module[{lam, x3, y3},
    Which[
      P == O, Q,
      Q == O, P,
      P[[1]] == Q[[1]] && P[[2]] == -Q[[2]], O,
      P[[1]] != Q[[1]],
      lam = Mod[(Q[[2]] - P[[2]]) PowerMod[Q[[1]] - P[[1]], p - 2, p], p];
      x3 = Mod[lam^2 - P[[1]] - Q[[1]], p];
      y3 = Mod[lam (P[[1]] - x3) - P[[2]], p];
      {x3, y3},
      True,
      lam = Mod[(3 P[[1]]^2 + a) PowerMod[2 P[[2]], p - 2, p], p];
      x3 = Mod[lam^2 - 2 P[[1]], p];
      y3 = Mod[lam (P[[1]] - x3) - P[[2]], p];
      {x3, y3}
    ]
  ];

  (* Define the Eliptic function for multiplying a point by an integer *)
  Eliptic[k_Integer, P_List] := Module[
    {n = k, Q = O, current = P},
    While[n > 0,
      If[EvenQ[n], 
        current = EllipticAdd[current, current]; 
        n = n/2,
        Q = EllipticAdd[Q, current]; 
        n = n - 1
      ]
    ];
    Q
  ];

  (* Compute the hash of the text (document) *)
  EE = Hash[txt, "MD5"];

  (* Generate the point R *)
  R = Eliptic[k, P];

  (* Derive signature components r and s *)
  r = Mod[R[[1]], q];
  If[r == 0, Return[Null]];
  s = PowerMod[k, -1, q] (EE + r s) mod q;
  If[s == 0, Return[Null]];

  (* Return the signature *)
  {r, s}
];

